description: From Middle English see-banke, se-banke, see banke, equivalent to sea +‎ bank.

entries.meaning: A bank or mole to defend against the sea.
examples: So strong is the barrier which these sea-borne sands oppose to the river-borne ooze, that as soon as a seabank is built — as the projectors of the Victoria County have built them — across any part of the estuary, the mud caught by it soon 'warps' the space within into firm and rich dry land.
